			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">CadC protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>According to the proposed model , LysP and CadC interact via their transmembrane domains in the absence of lysine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21441513" target="_blank">21441513</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of lysine , LysP releases CadC and CadC becomes susceptible to activation by low pH. These Ô¨Åndings suggest that LysP has an additional regulatory function , which is typical for so-called trigger transporters ( 54 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21441513" target="_blank">21441513</a>]<br></li>
<li>Conversely , for the K3N sensor CadC , a cluster of K3N-only residues is conserved in the N-terminal ` arm ' , while others are found in the K3 and KR helices ( cf. Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>At first glance , FeoA ( 75 amino acid resi-dues ) and FeoB ( 773 amino acid residues ) seemed to be comparable to the cadmium export system ( cadAC ) , in which one relatively large membrane protein , CadA ( 727 amino acid residues ) , and CadC ( 122 amino acid residues ) catalyze the ATP-driven export of Cd2 '' ( 22 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8407793" target="_blank">8407793</a>]<br></li>
<li>The spectrum for C11G-CadC is also characterized by Co ( II ) binding to both the K3N and K5 sites , except that the strong blue shift in the low energy transitions suggests that just three cysteine thiolate ^ Co ( II ) coordination bonds are formed in the mutant K3N Co ( II ) complex , i.e. , Cys11 is a ligand [ 39 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li>
<li>Plasmid pPH2249 differs from pPH2200 by the presence of a frameshift mutation at the ClaI site at nucleotide 1031 ( 53 amino acids from the amino terminus of CadC ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1370290" target="_blank">1370290</a>]<br></li>
<li>The comparisons are summarized below the sequences as follows : ( i ) asterisks correspond to residues that are conserved between CadC and at least one of the other two proteins , ( ii ) lowercase letters correspond to residues that are identical between CadC and at least one of the other proteins , and ( iii ) capital letters correspond to residues that are identical in all three proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1370290" target="_blank">1370290</a>]<br></li>
<li>The CadC protein is schematically shown and labeled with its three separate domains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8808945" target="_blank">8808945</a>]<br></li>
<li>Equal molarities of the purified KdpD derivatives and , as controls , two soluble signaling proteins , the purified periplasmic domain of CadC ( sensor domain of a membrane-bound transcriptional activator in E. coli ) 38 and LuxU ( histidine-containing phosphotransfer protein ( HPt ) in Vibrio harveyi ) 39 were spotted in equal volumes onto a nitrocellulose membrane , which was incubated with purified UspC in buffer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19101563" target="_blank">19101563</a>]<br></li>
<li>One of these proteins is the membrane-integrated transcriptional activator CadC , which consists of a periplasmic sensor domain and a cytoplasmic DNA-binding domain .38 In accordance with our in vitro observations , comparative studies with E. coli wild type cells and a ŒîuspC mutant indicated that UspC boosts KdpFABC production in response to salt stress , but UspC is without effect under K + limitation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19101563" target="_blank">19101563</a>]<br></li>
<li>This outer domain senses , either directly or indirectly , fluctuations in periplasmic pH resulting in an unspecified alteration of CadC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1370290" target="_blank">1370290</a>]<br></li>
<li>The model proposed by Watson et ai ( 1992 ) postulates that the extemal domain of CadC senses fiuctuations in periplasmic pH resulting in conformational modifications of CadC which ailow the amino-terminal cytoplasmic domain to function as a transcriptional activator specific for the cad operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8057841" target="_blank">8057841</a>]<br></li>
<li>A region of about 100 amino acids at the amino terminus of CadC was found to be similar to the carboxy termini of several bacterial proteins known to be transcriptional activators ( 31 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1370290" target="_blank">1370290</a>]<br></li>
<li>The predicted amino terminal region of the cadC gene product ( CadC ) resembles the carboxy-terminal domain of prokaryotic transcriptional activators involved in environmental sensing .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1370290" target="_blank">1370290</a>]<br></li>
<li>The predicted amino-terminal domain of CadC displays high homoiogy to the carboxy-terminal region of prokaryotic transcriptional activators involved in environmental sensing , including PhoP from Bacillus subtilis , OmpR from E. coti , VirG from Agrobacter-ium tumefaciens and ToxR from Vibrio choierae ( Watson e ( ai , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8057841" target="_blank">8057841</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although a direct interaction between CadC and Pcad has not been demonstrated , the genetic evidence presented here along with the similarity between CadC and other DNA-binding proteins strongly suggests that such an interaction is responsible for pH-induced transcriptional response .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1370290" target="_blank">1370290</a>]<br></li>
<li>Does CadC , like ToxR , have both cytoplasmic and periplasmic domains ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1370290" target="_blank">1370290</a>]<br></li>
<li>The basic premise of the model is that like ToxR , the amino domain of CadC is a DNA-binding domain and resides in the cytoplasm with one or more domains localized in the outer face of the cytoplasmic membrane or periplasmic space .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1370290" target="_blank">1370290</a>]<br></li>
<li>Specifically , is CadC a DNA-binding protein ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1370290" target="_blank">1370290</a>]<br></li>
<li>Unlike the other members of this class , however , the DNA-binding domain in ToxR , like in CadC , is located at its amino terminus .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1370290" target="_blank">1370290</a>]<br></li>
<li>ToxR , however , differs from the OmpR class of response proteins in at least two fundamental ways : it is membrane bound , and like CadC , the conserved DNA-binding domain is at the amino terminus ( 23 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1370290" target="_blank">1370290</a>]<br></li>
<li>The mechanism by which CadC functions to activate Pcad is not clear ; however the observation that its amino terminus is similar to the carboxyl DNA-binding domain of a group of transcriptional activators ( OmpR-like proteins ) suggests that a CadC-DNA interaction is involved ( 24 , 31 , 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1370290" target="_blank">1370290</a>]<br></li>
<li>The amino terminus of CadC protein has signiÔ¨Åcant homology to the DNA-binding domain of a number of activators and is overall most similar to ToxR of Vibrio cholerae ( 16 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7836317" target="_blank">7836317</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
